Asclepias incarnata

   [12484.jpg]
    Authority   L.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Asteridae:Gentianales:Asclepiadaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names swamp milkweed, swamp silkweed, white indian hemp
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 12484

   Notes
   DESCRIPTION: It is a semiaquatic, herbaceous, perennial reaching 30-90
   cm in height. All plant parts contain with milky sap. USE: Young
   shoots, flowers and leaves may be cooked with several changes of water
   and eaten. Stem fibres have been suggested as substitutes for flax and
   hemp. The roots have medicinal properties. It is grown as garden
   ornamental attracting butterflies. It is poisonous to sheep. GROWING
   PERIOD: Perennial. COMMON NAMES: Swamp milkweed, Swamp silkweed, White
   Indian hemp. FURTHER INF: It occurs in a range of wet conditions from
   standing water to saturated soil. It is common in wet places, such as
   low swampy ground, sphagnum bogs, stream banks, pond shores, and
   floodplains of lakes, waterways, marshes, swamps, wet areas in
   grassland and in low wet woods. It is a colonizer. It has
   wind-dispersed seeds and can self-fertilize.

   Sources
   http://www.ibiblio.org/herbmed/eclectic/cook/ASCLEPIAS_INCARNATA.htm
   http://www.fs.fed.us/database/feis/plants/forb/ascinc/

